# Literature Review: Navigating the Latest Developments in China's Cybersecurity Law

## Introduction

China's new Cybersecurity Law (CSL), which came into operation on June 1, 2017, has significant
implications for various industries, including IT, media, and telecommunications. This literature review
aims to provide a comprehensive analysis of the latest legal developments, cases, and issues relevant to
the IT, media, and telecommunications industries in China. It explores the impact of the CSL on these
industries and identifies potential knowledge gaps that require further research.

## Cybersecurity Law in China

The Cybersecurity Law (CSL) in China has attracted significant attention due to its potential impact on
various industries, including IT, media, and telecommunications. The Chinese government has issued a
series of draft measures, guidelines, and regulations to implement the CSL (Kennedy & Lee, 2017, p. 1).
These developments have generated concerns and uncertainties among businesses operating in China.

## Implications for the IT industry

The CSL has several implications for the IT industry in China. One of the key provisions of the CSL is
the requirement for network operators to store user data within China's territory (Kennedy & Lee, 2017,
p. 1). This provision has raised concerns among multinational IT companies operating in China, as it may
impact their ability to transfer data across borders and comply with other jurisdictions' data protection
laws.
Furthermore, the CSL introduces strict cybersecurity requirements for network operators, including the
obligation to implement security measures and report cybersecurity incidents (Kennedy & Lee, 2017,
p. 1). Complying with these requirements may pose challenges for IT companies, especially those with
complex IT infrastructure and extensive networks.

## Implications for the media industry

The media industry in China is also affected by the CSL. The law imposes certain restrictions on online
content and platforms, aiming to regulate the dissemination of information (Kennedy & Lee, 2017, p.
1). Online media companies are required to obtain licenses to operate and comply with specific content
review procedures.
The CSL also introduces provisions that hold service providers accountable for the content posted by their
